## Running DebOps

Load the ``debops-find-source`` skill if you need to inspect role
defaults or playbook code. Load the ``debops-find-documentation``
skill to look up subcommand or role documentation. Load the
``debops-debug`` skill when diagnosing playbook failures.

### 1. Playbook hierarchy

Playbooks are organized in layers executed sequentially:

```
debops run site
  ├── layer/net       (network infra)
  ├── layer/sys       (system plumbing)
  ├── layer/common    (all hosts: ~50 roles)
  ├── layer/env       (programming languages)
  ├── layer/srv       (databases, webservers, mail, etc.)
  ├── layer/app       (user-facing applications)
  ├── layer/virt      (virtualization)
  ├── layer/hw        (hardware)
  └── layer/agent     (monitoring agents)
```

Target a single service via its inventory group:

```sh
debops check service/nginx -l webserver1
```

### 2. Targeting specific roles with --tags

Every role has an inclusion tag ``role::<name>`` and an exclusion tag
``skip::<name>``. Finer-grained sub-tags exist per role:

```sh
# Run only the nginx role
debops check service/nginx --tags role::nginx

# Run only sshd config (skip known_hosts)
debops check service/sshd --tags role::sshd:config

# Run everything except ferm
debops check site --skip-tags skip::ferm

# Run a specific role across the full site
debops check site --tags role::pam_access
```

Common sub-tags: ``role::<name>:config``, ``meta::facts``,
``meta::provision``.

### 3. Ad-hoc Ansible commands

Use ``debops exec`` to run single Ansible modules within the project
environment:

```sh
debops exec host -m setup
debops exec host -m ansible.builtin.ping
```

This is equivalent to ``ansible host -m setup`` but with the project's
inventory, collection paths, and configuration pre-loaded.

### 4. Fully-qualified playbook names

```sh
debops check debops.debops.site
debops check debops.debops.service.nginx
```

### 5. Playbook sets (modern projects)

If the project defines playbook sets in its configuration, use them as
shorthand:

```sh
debops run webservice -l webserver1
```

Check ``.debops/conf.d/`` for definitions.

### 6. Utility playbooks

Special-purpose playbooks for host lifecycle:

```sh
# Bootstrap a fresh minimal Debian host
# NOTE: might require the root password via --ask-pass.
# The agent cannot handle interactive prompts.
# Direct the user to run this command manually.
debops run bootstrap -l newhost --user root --ask-pass

# Reboot hosts (optionally after upgrade)
debops run reboot -l hostname

# Dump all host variables for debugging
debops run tools/debug -l hostname
```

### 7. Safety

Always use ``debops check`` (dry-run with diff) by default. Only use
``debops run`` when the user explicitly confirms.

### 8. Passwords and secrets

The agent cannot handle interactive password prompts. If a command requires
``--ask-pass``, ``--become`` with a password, or any other interactive
authentication, stop and direct the user to run that specific command manually
outside of the session. Never prompt the user for a password within the chat.
